 way toward remedying the need for a sustained examination of blood ties, kinship, gender, and sexuality, and the prominence of these themes in Malory's work. They concentrate in particular upon the analyses of sexuality and sexual activity (and itslack or erasure) and the significance of blood (and blood-shedding) in the Morte Darthur, as well as the interconnections with gender (biological sex) and familial ("blood") relations in the Morte, its sources and its later reworkings. The result is a wide-ranging investigation into related but distinctive thematic preoccupations, including the national and kinship affiliations of Malorian knights, sibling relationships, deviant sexuality, and blood-spilling in martial and intimate contexts. Contributors: Christina Francis, Megan G. Leitch, Helen Phillips, Carolyne Larrington, Lydia A. Fletcher, Kate McClune, Sally Mapstone, Caitlyn Schwartz, Maria SachikoCecire, Anna Caughey, Catherine LaFarge  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthurian Literature.  aBlood Ties.  aGender.  aMalory.  aNational Affiliations.  aSexuality.1 aCaughey, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecire, Maria Sachiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFletcher, Lydia A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Lydia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancis, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLa Farge, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaFarge, Catherine La, econtributor.4ctb